title: Network Interoperability Assignment
abstract: <div class="abstract-content"><div class="text full">ITS&nbsp;213&nbsp;-&nbsp;Network&nbsp;Interoperability<br><div><span>Objectives</span></div><div><span>Explain the role of protocols and standards organizations in facilitating interoperability in network communications.</span></div><div>In this activity, you will determine ways to communicate when standards are not present or agreed upon. You will also resolve a communication issue by establishing standards for communication.</div><br>Background&nbsp;/&nbsp;Scenario<br><div>You have just purchased a new automobile for your personal use. After driving the car for a week or so, you find that it is not properly functioning. After discussing the problem with several of your peers, you decide to take it to a highly recommended automotive repair facility. It is the only repair facility located in close proximity to you. When you arrive at the repair facility, you find that all of the mechanics speak another language. You are having difficulty explaining the automobiles performance problems, but the repairs really need to be done. You are not sure you can drive it back home to</div><div>research other options. You must find a way to work with the repair facility to ensure your automobile is properly repaired.</div><div>How will you communicate with the mechanics in this firm?</div><div>Design a communications model to ensure that the car is properly repaired.</div><br>What steps did you identify as important to communicating your repair request?<br>Justify your answer.</div></div>

title: Activity 1
abstract: <div class="abstract-content" data-image-width="440" data-image-height="293"><div class="media"><img class="image-resource" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/Large_bonfire.jpg/440px-Large_bonfire.jpg" style="width: 100%;"></div><div class="text"><p><b>Fire</b>&nbsp;is the rapid&nbsp;oxidation&nbsp;of a material in the&nbsp;exothermic&nbsp;chemical process of&nbsp;combustion, releasing&nbsp;heat,&nbsp;light, and various reaction&nbsp;products.<sup id="cite_ref-1">[1]</sup>&nbsp;Slower oxidative processes like&nbsp;rusting&nbsp;or&nbsp;digestion&nbsp;are not included by this definition.</p><p>The&nbsp;&nbsp;is the visible portion of the fire. If hot enough, the gases may become ionized to produce&nbsp;plasma.<sup id="cite_ref-2">[2]</sup>&nbsp;Depending on the substances alight, and any impurities outside, the&nbsp;color&nbsp;of the flame and the fire's&nbsp;intensity&nbsp;will be different.</p><p>Fire in its most common form can result in&nbsp;conflagration, which has the potential to cause physical damage through&nbsp;burning. Fire is an important process that affects ecological systems across the globe. The positive effects of fire include stimulating growth and maintaining various ecological systems. Fire has been used by humans for cooking, generating heat, signaling, and propulsion purposes. The negative effects of fire include water contamination, soil erosion, atmospheric pollution and hazard to life and property.<sup id="cite_ref-3">[3]</sup></p><br><div>Figure 1. &nbsp;A fire.</div><br><div>Figure 2. Another fire.</div><br><p>Fires start when a&nbsp;flammable&nbsp;and/or a combustible&nbsp;material, in combination with a sufficient quantity of an&nbsp;oxidizer&nbsp;such as oxygen gas or another oxygen-rich compound (though non-oxygen oxidizers exist that can replace oxygen), is exposed to a source of&nbsp;heat&nbsp;or ambient&nbsp;temperature&nbsp;above the&nbsp;flash point&nbsp;for thefuel/oxidizer mix, and is able to sustain a rate of rapid oxidation that produces a&nbsp;chain reaction. This is commonly called the&nbsp;fire tetrahedron. Fire cannot exist without all of these elements in place and in the right proportions. For example, a flammable liquid will start burning only if the fuel and oxygen are in the right proportions. Some fuel-oxygen mixes may require a&nbsp;catalyst, a substance that is not directly involved in any&nbsp;chemical&nbsp;reaction during combustion, but which enables the reactants to combust more readily.</p><p>Once ignited, a chain reaction must take place whereby fires can sustain their own heat by the further release of heat energy in the process of combustion and may propagate, provided there is a continuous supply of an oxidizer and fuel.</p><p>If the oxidizer is oxygen from the surrounding air, the presence of a force of&nbsp;gravity, or of some similar force caused by acceleration, is necessary to produceconvection, which removes combustion products and brings a supply of oxygen to the fire. Without gravity, a fire rapidly surrounds itself with its own combustion products and non-oxidizing gases from the air, which exclude oxygen and&nbsp;extinguish&nbsp;it. Because of this, the risk of fire in a&nbsp;spacecraft&nbsp;is small when it is&nbsp;coastingin inertial flight. Of course, this does not apply if oxygen is supplied to the fire by some process other than thermal convection.</p><br><span>Has your life ever been changed irreversibly by a fire? &nbsp;Who started the fire?</span><br><span>(Hint: We didn't start the fire.)</span></div></div>

abstract: <div class="abstract-content" data-image-width="1000" data-image-height="5882"><div class="media"><img class="image-resource" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e6/1000px-Atmosphere_layers-en.PNG" style="width: 100%;"></div><div class="text"><b>Outer space</b><span>, or simply&nbsp;</span><b>space</b><span>, is the void that exists between&nbsp;</span>celestial bodies<span>, including the&nbsp;</span>Earth<span>.</span><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDainton2001132.E2.80.93133_1-0">[1]</sup><span>&nbsp;It is not completely empty, but consists of a&nbsp;</span>hard vacuum<span>containing a low density of particles: predominantly a&nbsp;</span>plasma<span>&nbsp;of&nbsp;</span>hydrogen<span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;</span>helium<span>, as well as&nbsp;</span>electromagnetic radiation<span>,&nbsp;</span>magnetic fields<span>, and&nbsp;</span>neutrinos<span>. The baseline temperature, as set by the&nbsp;</span>background radiation<span>&nbsp;from the&nbsp;</span>Big Bang<span>, is 2.7&nbsp;</span>kelvin<span>&nbsp;(K).</span><sup id="cite_ref-CBE2008_2-0">[2]</sup><span>&nbsp;Plasma with a density of less than one hydrogen atom per cubic meter and a temperature of millions of kelvin in the&nbsp;</span>space between galaxies<span>&nbsp;accounts for most of the&nbsp;</span>baryonic (ordinary) matter<span>&nbsp;in outer space; local concentrations have condensed into&nbsp;</span>stars<span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;</span>galaxies<span>. In most galaxies, observations provide evidence that 90% of the mass is in an unknown form, called&nbsp;</span>dark matter<span>, which interacts with other matter through&nbsp;</span>gravitational<span>&nbsp;but not&nbsp;</span>electromagnetic<span>&nbsp;forces.</span><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFreedmanKaufmann2005573.2C_599-601_3-0">[3]</sup><sup id="cite_ref-Trimble_1987_4-0">[4]</sup><span>&nbsp;Data indicates that the majority of the&nbsp;</span>mass-energy<span>&nbsp;in the&nbsp;</span>observable Universe<span>is a poorly understood&nbsp;</span>vacuum energy<span>&nbsp;of space which astronomers label&nbsp;</span>dark energy<span>.</span><sup id="cite_ref-nasa_darkenergy_5-0">[5]</sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFreedmanKaufmann2005650-653_6-0">[6]</sup><span>&nbsp;Intergalactic space takes up most of the volume of the&nbsp;</span>Universe<span>, but even galaxies and star systems consist almost entirely of empty space.</span><br><p>There is no firm boundary where space begins. However the&nbsp;Krmn line, at an altitude of 100&nbsp;km (62&nbsp;mi) above&nbsp;sea level,<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEO.27Leary200984_7-0">[7]</sup>&nbsp;is conventionally used as the start of outer space in space treaties and for aerospace records keeping. The framework for international&nbsp;space law&nbsp;was established by the&nbsp;Outer Space Treaty, which was passed by the&nbsp;United Nations&nbsp;in 1967. This treaty precludes any claims of national sovereignty and permits all states to freely explore outer space. In 1979, theMoon Treaty&nbsp;made the surfaces of objects such as planets, as well as the orbital space around these bodies, the jurisdiction of the international community. Despite the drafting of UN resolutions for the peaceful uses of outer space,&nbsp;anti-satellite weapons&nbsp;have been tested in Earth orbit.</p><p>Humans began the physical exploration of space during the 20th century with the advent of high-altitude&nbsp;balloon flights, followed by manned&nbsp;rocket launches.&nbsp;Earth orbit&nbsp;was first achieved by&nbsp;Yuri Gagarin&nbsp;of the Soviet Union in 1961 and&nbsp;unmanned spacecraft&nbsp;have since reached all of the known&nbsp;planets&nbsp;in the&nbsp;Solar System. Achieving&nbsp;low Earth orbit&nbsp;requires a minimum velocity of 28,100&nbsp;km/h (17,500&nbsp;mph), much faster than any conventional aircraft. Outer space represents a challenging environment for human exploration because of the dual hazards of vacuum and&nbsp;radiation.&nbsp;Microgravity&nbsp;has a negative effect on human&nbsp;physiology, causing&nbsp;muscle atrophy&nbsp;and&nbsp;bone loss.&nbsp;Space travel&nbsp;has been limited to low Earth orbit and the&nbsp;Moon&nbsp;for manned flight, and the&nbsp;vicinity of the Solar System&nbsp;for unmanned vehicles. In August 2012,&nbsp;Voyager 1&nbsp;became the first man-made craft to enter interstellar space.</p><br><div>Figure 2. &nbsp;A picture of something you might find in outer space.</div><br><span>Do you think you will ever go to outer space? &nbsp;Why?</span><br><span>Do you prefer astronauts or cosmonauts? &nbsp;Why?</span></div></div>

In August 2012,&nbsp;Voyager 1&nbsp;became the first man-made craft to enter interstellar space.</p><br><div>Figure 2. &nbsp;A picture of something you might find in outer space.</div><br><span>Do you think you will ever go to outer space? &nbsp;Why?</span><br><span>Do you prefer astronauts or cosmonauts? &nbsp;Why?</span></div></div>

title: Beginning Yoga
abstract: <div class="abstract-content" data-image-width="300" data-image-height="300"><div class="media"><img class="image-resource" src="http://images.meredith.com/fitness/images/2007/01/ss_mountain.jpg" style="width: 100%;"></div><div class="text"><span>For each pose, follow the model and attach a photo of yourself completing the same pose.</span><br><span>Mountain Pose</span><br><ul><li><span>Stand tall with feet together, shoulders relaxed, weight evenly distributed through your soles, arms at sides.</span><br></li><li><span>Take a deep breath and raise your hands overhead, palms facing each other with arms straight. Reach up toward the sky with your fingertips.</span></li></ul><br><span>Instructor Feedback</span><br><span>Downward Dog</span><br><ul><li><span>Start on all fours with hands directly under shoulders, knees under hips.</span><br></li><p></p><p></p><li><span>Walk hands a few inches forward and spread fingers wide, pressing palms into mat.</span><br></li><li><span>Curl toes under and slowly press hips toward ceiling, bringing your body into an inverted V, pressing shoulders away from ears. Feet should be hip-width apart, knees slightly bent.</span><br></li><li><span>Hold for 3 full breaths.</span></li></ul><br><span>Instructor Feedback</span><br><span>&nbsp;</span><span><span>W</span><span>arrior</span></span><br><ul><li><span>Stand with legs 3 to 4 feet apart, turning right foot out 90 degrees and left foot in slightly.</span><br></li><p></p><p></p><li><span>Bring your hands to your hips and relax your shoulders, then extend arms out to the sides, palms down.</span><br></li><li><span>Bend right knee 90 degrees, keeping knee over ankle; gaze out over right hand. Stay for 1 minute.</span><br></li><li><span>Switch sides and repeat.</span></li></ul><br><span>Instructor Feedback</span></div></div>

title: Activity 3
abstract: <div class="abstract-content"><div class="text full"><span>Annual Assessment of Student Outcomes</span><br><div><span>School of Behavioral Sciences BA in Sociology</span><br></div><div><span>BA Sociology - (44 units)</span></div><div><span>The Sociology major prepares graduates for employment in social service careers, and for graduate study in Sociology, Criminology, Social Work, and Anthropology. &nbsp;Students select at least one area of concentration within the major. Students are encouraged to pursue a complimentary minor. &nbsp;Students may complete a double major in Psychology and Sociology by substituting overlapping courses. &nbsp;Students may also complete a Psychology or Christian Behavioral Science minor.</span></div><br><span>'12-'13 Sociology Program Final Report</span><br><div><span>&nbsp;1. &nbsp;Final Report: The program evaluated the progress on the move away from straight points grading methodology to a learner-centered set of academic satndards allowing students to decide on the level of effort they wanted to demonstrate beyond the minimum requirements of the assignment.&nbsp;&nbsp;One of the MOAs was the documentation of voluntary rough drafts and edited assignments. &nbsp;In the SOC 213 Introduction to Sociology courses in SP'09, 65% of the students from two sections (N = 80) voluntarily posted assignment efforts that were above minimum requirements&nbsp;(most were from SOC 213 Section B). &nbsp;In addition, 35% completed small outside assignments from the text or from outside reading. &nbsp; Evidence is documented in the Messages feature in Blackboard and will be compiled and analyzed in the Spring of 2010.</span></div><div><span>In SOC 338 Group Dynamics the evidence was also very clear in the group project. &nbsp;90% of the students (N = 16) documented efforts well beyond minimum expectations. &nbsp;Students were required to document their individual research efforts as if they were doing the project individually rather than in a group. &nbsp;The results were seen in impressive powerPoint presentations (examples attached) containing increased depth and breadth. &nbsp; In addition, many of these students self-reflected on the value of the group experience and how it stretched them. &nbsp;(See attachments)</span></div><div><span>The academic portfolio template is still in the earliest stages of development; the goal of having it ready by the end of the SP'09 semester was unrealistic. &nbsp;It will be the foundation for the identification of General Education outcomes in this program. &nbsp;An undergraduate academic handbook is going to be a part of this portfolio template, allowing tracking of student learning across the entire degree experience, thus providing opportunity for a year-by-year assessment of specific USOs, rather than limiting the evaluation to the senior capstone.</span></div><div><span>Finally, as we continue to project growth in the Sociology Major Program, the attached article from the Chronicle of Higher Ed gives a brief overview of the potential for a Master's Degree Program. &nbsp;The chart is especially relevant as we continue to work on a tradtitional Sociology Major, as well as a preparatory program for student desiring a Social Work Degree. (see article attachment)</span></div><br><div><span>The program continues the process of moving away from using grades on exams, assignments, and projects. &nbsp;Our outcomes are listed below:</span></div><div><span>PSO #6);&nbsp;We established an academic standard of effort for each letter grade&nbsp;(See the Student Performance Standards attached). &nbsp;The goal was to help them understand that getting the correct answers was not enough to characterize one as an A student. &nbsp;Data for the measure of success was drawn from the Blackboard Learning Management System; students posted evidence of their learning process across the semester. &nbsp;Success was measured by the number of edits and extra (non-assigned evidence) students post from assignments, with a focus on posting that goes beyond minimum posting requirements. &nbsp;The outcomes were encouraging! &nbsp;78% of the Introduction to Sociology classes in SP'08 (N=80, n=65) posted more than the minimum requirements, meaning less missing or late assignments, and compared to the same courses, using the same assignments from SP'07 - rough drafts encouraged, but not required. &nbsp;Less than 50% of the students in two sections created a draft.</span></div><div><span>PSO #4); Continued assessment of written communication skills - The Sociology program continues to put emphasis on quality writing and APA style. &nbsp;We are seeing most of our undergraduate sociology students using proofreading &amp; editing skills. &nbsp;Our intent was to use students self-perception of their Internet, research writing and information literacy skills by completing an anonymous, online survey. &nbsp;This survey was to be used in courses across the SBS disciplines; not enough faculty participated to draw any significant conclusions. &nbsp;In addition, the survey instrument had some serious flaws. &nbsp;We may try this again in the fall using a new survey instrument.</span></div><div><span>PSO #5, the research process; the focus is on library and research skills and information literacy. &nbsp;Students had the opportunity to practice specific elements of research, editing skills, APA, and demonstrate their ability to use the library resources. &nbsp;The MOS was based on evidence from visual essay projects from SOC 345 Social Problems. &nbsp;(See the rubric &amp; PowerPoint samples of A, B &amp; C level work attached.)</span></div><div><span>Also, data was drawn from visual essay projects from SOC 338 Deviant Behavior FA'07, SOC 338 Group Dynamics &amp; Social Movements SP'08 &amp; SOC381ae (Sample of A effort attached). &nbsp; 82% of these upper-division students posted drafts and significant research process evidence (See attachments)</span></div></div></div>

&nbsp;78% of the Introduction to Sociology classes in SP'08 (N=80, n=65) posted more than the minimum requirements, meaning less missing or late assignments, and compared to the same courses, using the same assignments from SP'07 - rough drafts encouraged, but not required. &nbsp;Less than 50% of the students in two sections created a draft.</span></div><div><span>PSO #4); Continued assessment of written communication skills - The Sociology program continues to put emphasis on quality writing and APA style. &nbsp;We are seeing most of our undergraduate sociology students using proofreading &amp; editing skills. &nbsp;Our intent was to use students self-perception of their Internet, research writing and information literacy skills by completing an anonymous, online survey. &nbsp;This survey was to be used in courses across the SBS disciplines; not enough faculty participated to draw any significant conclusions. &nbsp;In addition, the survey instrument had some serious flaws. &nbsp;We may try this again in the fall using a new survey instrument.</span></div><div><span>PSO #5, the research process; the focus is on library and research skills and information literacy. &nbsp;Students had the opportunity to practice specific elements of research, editing skills, APA, and demonstrate their ability to use the library resources. &nbsp;The MOS was based on evidence from visual essay projects from SOC 345 Social Problems. &nbsp;(See the rubric &amp; PowerPoint samples of A, B &amp; C level work attached.)</span></div><div><span>Also, data was drawn from visual essay projects from SOC 338 Deviant Behavior FA'07, SOC 338 Group Dynamics &amp; Social Movements SP'08 &amp; SOC381ae (Sample of A effort attached). &nbsp; 82% of these upper-division students posted drafts and significant research process evidence (See attachments)</span></div></div></div>

title: Activity 1
abstract: <div class="abstract-content" data-image-width="440" data-image-height="293"><div class="media"><img class="image-resource" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/Large_bonfire.jpg/440px-Large_bonfire.jpg" style="width: 100%;"></div><div class="text"><p><b>Fire</b>&nbsp;is the rapid&nbsp;oxidation&nbsp;of a material in the&nbsp;exothermic&nbsp;chemical process of&nbsp;combustion, releasing&nbsp;heat,&nbsp;light, and various reaction&nbsp;products.<sup id="cite_ref-1">[1]</sup>&nbsp;Slower oxidative processes like&nbsp;rusting&nbsp;or&nbsp;digestion&nbsp;are not included by this definition.</p><p>The&nbsp;&nbsp;is the visible portion of the fire. If hot enough, the gases may become ionized to produce&nbsp;plasma.<sup id="cite_ref-2">[2]</sup>&nbsp;Depending on the substances alight, and any impurities outside, the&nbsp;color&nbsp;of the flame and the fire's&nbsp;intensity&nbsp;will be different.</p><p>Fire in its most common form can result in&nbsp;conflagration, which has the potential to cause physical damage through&nbsp;burning. Fire is an important process that affects ecological systems across the globe. The positive effects of fire include stimulating growth and maintaining various ecological systems. Fire has been used by humans for cooking, generating heat, signaling, and propulsion purposes. The negative effects of fire include water contamination, soil erosion, atmospheric pollution and hazard to life and property.<sup id="cite_ref-3">[3]</sup></p><br><div>Figure 1. &nbsp;A fire.</div><br><div>Figure 2. Another fire.</div><br><p>Fires start when a&nbsp;flammable&nbsp;and/or a combustible&nbsp;material, in combination with a sufficient quantity of an&nbsp;oxidizer&nbsp;such as oxygen gas or another oxygen-rich compound (though non-oxygen oxidizers exist that can replace oxygen), is exposed to a source of&nbsp;heat&nbsp;or ambient&nbsp;temperature&nbsp;above the&nbsp;flash point&nbsp;for thefuel/oxidizer mix, and is able to sustain a rate of rapid oxidation that produces a&nbsp;chain reaction. This is commonly called the&nbsp;fire tetrahedron. Fire cannot exist without all of these elements in place and in the right proportions. For example, a flammable liquid will start burning only if the fuel and oxygen are in the right proportions. Some fuel-oxygen mixes may require a&nbsp;catalyst, a substance that is not directly involved in any&nbsp;chemical&nbsp;reaction during combustion, but which enables the reactants to combust more readily.</p><p>Once ignited, a chain reaction must take place whereby fires can sustain their own heat by the further release of heat energy in the process of combustion and may propagate, provided there is a continuous supply of an oxidizer and fuel.</p><p>If the oxidizer is oxygen from the surrounding air, the presence of a force of&nbsp;gravity, or of some similar force caused by acceleration, is necessary to produceconvection, which removes combustion products and brings a supply of oxygen to the fire. Without gravity, a fire rapidly surrounds itself with its own combustion products and non-oxidizing gases from the air, which exclude oxygen and&nbsp;extinguish&nbsp;it. Because of this, the risk of fire in a&nbsp;spacecraft&nbsp;is small when it is&nbsp;coastingin inertial flight. Of course, this does not apply if oxygen is supplied to the fire by some process other than thermal convection.</p><br><span>Has your life ever been changed irreversibly by a fire? &nbsp;Who started the fire?</span><br><span>(Hint: We didn't start the fire.)</span></div></div>

title: Activity 2
abstract: <div class="abstract-content" data-image-width="1000" data-image-height="5882"><div class="media"><img class="image-resource" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e6/1000px-Atmosphere_layers-en.PNG" style="width: 100%;"></div><div class="text"><b>Outer space</b><span>, or simply&nbsp;</span><b>space</b><span>, is the void that exists between&nbsp;</span>celestial bodies<span>, including the&nbsp;</span>Earth<span>.</span><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDainton2001132.E2.80.93133_1-0">[1]</sup><span>&nbsp;It is not completely empty, but consists of a&nbsp;</span>hard vacuum<span>containing a low density of particles: predominantly a&nbsp;</span>plasma<span>&nbsp;of&nbsp;</span>hydrogen<span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;</span>helium<span>, as well as&nbsp;</span>electromagnetic radiation<span>,&nbsp;</span>magnetic fields<span>, and&nbsp;</span>neutrinos<span>. The baseline temperature, as set by the&nbsp;</span>background radiation<span>&nbsp;from the&nbsp;</span>Big Bang<span>, is 2.7&nbsp;</span>kelvin<span>&nbsp;(K).</span><sup id="cite_ref-CBE2008_2-0">[2]</sup><span>&nbsp;Plasma with a density of less than one hydrogen atom per cubic meter and a temperature of millions of kelvin in the&nbsp;</span>space between galaxies<span>&nbsp;accounts for most of the&nbsp;</span>baryonic (ordinary) matter<span>&nbsp;in outer space; local concentrations have condensed into&nbsp;</span>stars<span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;</span>galaxies<span>. In most galaxies, observations provide evidence that 90% of the mass is in an unknown form, called&nbsp;</span>dark matter<span>, which interacts with other matter through&nbsp;</span>gravitational<span>&nbsp;but not&nbsp;</span>electromagnetic<span>&nbsp;forces.</span><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFreedmanKaufmann2005573.2C_599-601_3-0">[3]</sup><sup id="cite_ref-Trimble_1987_4-0">[4]</sup><span>&nbsp;Data indicates that the majority of the&nbsp;</span>mass-energy<span>&nbsp;in the&nbsp;</span>observable Universe<span>is a poorly understood&nbsp;</span>vacuum energy<span>&nbsp;of space which astronomers label&nbsp;</span>dark energy<span>.</span><sup id="cite_ref-nasa_darkenergy_5-0">[5]</sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFreedmanKaufmann2005650-653_6-0">[6]</sup><span>&nbsp;Intergalactic space takes up most of the volume of the&nbsp;</span>Universe<span>, but even galaxies and star systems consist almost entirely of empty space.</span><br><p>There is no firm boundary where space begins. However the&nbsp;Krmn line, at an altitude of 100&nbsp;km (62&nbsp;mi) above&nbsp;sea level,<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEO.27Leary200984_7-0">[7]</sup>&nbsp;is conventionally used as the start of outer space in space treaties and for aerospace records keeping. The framework for international&nbsp;space law&nbsp;was established by the&nbsp;Outer Space Treaty, which was passed by the&nbsp;United Nations&nbsp;in 1967. This treaty precludes any claims of national sovereignty and permits all states to freely explore outer space. In 1979, theMoon Treaty&nbsp;made the surfaces of objects such as planets, as well as the orbital space around these bodies, the jurisdiction of the international community. Despite the drafting of UN resolutions for the peaceful uses of outer space,&nbsp;anti-satellite weapons&nbsp;have been tested in Earth orbit.</p><p>Humans began the physical exploration of space during the 20th century with the advent of high-altitude&nbsp;balloon flights, followed by manned&nbsp;rocket launches.&nbsp;Earth orbit&nbsp;was first achieved by&nbsp;Yuri Gagarin&nbsp;of the Soviet Union in 1961 and&nbsp;unmanned spacecraft&nbsp;have since reached all of the known&nbsp;planets&nbsp;in the&nbsp;Solar System. Achieving&nbsp;low Earth orbit&nbsp;requires a minimum velocity of 28,100&nbsp;km/h (17,500&nbsp;mph), much faster than any conventional aircraft. Outer space represents a challenging environment for human exploration because of the dual hazards of vacuum and&nbsp;radiation.&nbsp;Microgravity&nbsp;has a negative effect on human&nbsp;physiology, causing&nbsp;muscle atrophy&nbsp;and&nbsp;bone loss.&nbsp;Space travel&nbsp;has been limited to low Earth orbit and the&nbsp;Moon&nbsp;for manned flight, and the&nbsp;vicinity of the Solar System&nbsp;for unmanned vehicles. In August 2012,&nbsp;Voyager 1&nbsp;became the first man-made craft to enter interstellar space.</p><br><div>Figure 2. &nbsp;A picture of something you might find in outer space.</div><br><span>Do you think you will ever go to outer space? &nbsp;Why?</span><br><span>Do you prefer astronauts or cosmonauts? &nbsp;Why?</span></div></div>

The baseline temperature, as set by the&nbsp;</span>background radiation<span>&nbsp;from the&nbsp;</span>Big Bang<span>, is 2.7&nbsp;</span>kelvin<span>&nbsp;(K).</span><sup id="cite_ref-CBE2008_2-0">[2]</sup><span>&nbsp;Plasma with a density of less than one hydrogen atom per cubic meter and a temperature of millions of kelvin in the&nbsp;</span>space between galaxies<span>&nbsp;accounts for most of the&nbsp;</span>baryonic (ordinary) matter<span>&nbsp;in outer space; local concentrations have condensed into&nbsp;</span>stars<span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;</span>galaxies<span>. In most galaxies, observations provide evidence that 90% of the mass is in an unknown form, called&nbsp;</span>dark matter<span>, which interacts with other matter through&nbsp;</span>gravitational<span>&nbsp;but not&nbsp;</span>electromagnetic<span>&nbsp;forces.</span><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFreedmanKaufmann2005573.2C_599-601_3-0">[3]</sup><sup id="cite_ref-Trimble_1987_4-0">[4]</sup><span>&nbsp;Data indicates that the majority of the&nbsp;</span>mass-energy<span>&nbsp;in the&nbsp;</span>observable Universe<span>is a poorly understood&nbsp;</span>vacuum energy<span>&nbsp;of space which astronomers label&nbsp;</span>dark energy<span>.</span><sup id="cite_ref-nasa_darkenergy_5-0">[5]</sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFreedmanKaufmann2005650-653_6-0">[6]</sup><span>&nbsp;Intergalactic space takes up most of the volume of the&nbsp;</span>Universe<span>, but even galaxies and star systems consist almost entirely of empty space.</span><br><p>There is no firm boundary where space begins. However the&nbsp;Krmn line, at an altitude of 100&nbsp;km (62&nbsp;mi) above&nbsp;sea level,<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEO.27Leary200984_7-0">[7]</sup>&nbsp;is conventionally used as the start of outer space in space treaties and for aerospace records keeping. The framework for international&nbsp;space law&nbsp;was established by the&nbsp;Outer Space Treaty, which was passed by the&nbsp;United Nations&nbsp;in 1967. This treaty precludes any claims of national sovereignty and permits all states to freely explore outer space. In 1979, theMoon Treaty&nbsp;made the surfaces of objects such as planets, as well as the orbital space around these bodies, the jurisdiction of the international community. Despite the drafting of UN resolutions for the peaceful uses of outer space,&nbsp;anti-satellite weapons&nbsp;have been tested in Earth orbit.</p><p>Humans began the physical exploration of space during the 20th century with the advent of high-altitude&nbsp;balloon flights, followed by manned&nbsp;rocket launches.&nbsp;Earth orbit&nbsp;was first achieved by&nbsp;Yuri Gagarin&nbsp;of the Soviet Union in 1961 and&nbsp;unmanned spacecraft&nbsp;have since reached all of the known&nbsp;planets&nbsp;in the&nbsp;Solar System. Achieving&nbsp;low Earth orbit&nbsp;requires a minimum velocity of 28,100&nbsp;km/h (17,500&nbsp;mph), much faster than any conventional aircraft. Outer space represents a challenging environment for human exploration because of the dual hazards of vacuum and&nbsp;radiation.&nbsp;Microgravity&nbsp;has a negative effect on human&nbsp;physiology, causing&nbsp;muscle atrophy&nbsp;and&nbsp;bone loss.&nbsp;Space travel&nbsp;has been limited to low Earth orbit and the&nbsp;Moon&nbsp;for manned flight, and the&nbsp;vicinity of the Solar System&nbsp;for unmanned vehicles. In August 2012,&nbsp;Voyager 1&nbsp;became the first man-made craft to enter interstellar space.</p><br><div>Figure 2. &nbsp;A picture of something you might find in outer space.</div><br><span>Do you think you will ever go to outer space? &nbsp;Why?</span><br><span>Do you prefer astronauts or cosmonauts? &nbsp;Why?</span></div></div>

title: Activity 3
abstract: <div class="abstract-content"><div class="text full"><span>Annual Assessment of Student Outcomes</span><br><div><span>School of Behavioral Sciences BA in Sociology</span><br></div><div><span>BA Sociology - (44 units)</span></div><div><span>The Sociology major prepares graduates for employment in social service careers, and for graduate study in Sociology, Criminology, Social Work, and Anthropology. &nbsp;Students select at least one area of concentration within the major. Students are encouraged to pursue a complimentary minor. &nbsp;Students may complete a double major in Psychology and Sociology by substituting overlapping courses. &nbsp;Students may also complete a Psychology or Christian Behavioral Science minor.</span></div><br><span>'12-'13 Sociology Program Final Report</span><br><div><span>&nbsp;1. &nbsp;Final Report: The program evaluated the progress on the move away from straight points grading methodology to a learner-centered set of academic satndards allowing students to decide on the level of effort they wanted to demonstrate beyond the minimum requirements of the assignment.&nbsp;&nbsp;One of the MOAs was the documentation of voluntary rough drafts and edited assignments. &nbsp;In the SOC 213 Introduction to Sociology courses in SP'09, 65% of the students from two sections (N = 80) voluntarily posted assignment efforts that were above minimum requirements&nbsp;(most were from SOC 213 Section B). &nbsp;In addition, 35% completed small outside assignments from the text or from outside reading. &nbsp; Evidence is documented in the Messages feature in Blackboard and will be compiled and analyzed in the Spring of 2010.</span></div><div><span>In SOC 338 Group Dynamics the evidence was also very clear in the group project. &nbsp;90% of the students (N = 16) documented efforts well beyond minimum expectations. &nbsp;Students were required to document their individual research efforts as if they were doing the project individually rather than in a group. &nbsp;The results were seen in impressive powerPoint presentations (examples attached) containing increased depth and breadth. &nbsp; In addition, many of these students self-reflected on the value of the group experience and how it stretched them. &nbsp;(See attachments)</span></div><div><span>The academic portfolio template is still in the earliest stages of development; the goal of having it ready by the end of the SP'09 semester was unrealistic. &nbsp;It will be the foundation for the identification of General Education outcomes in this program. &nbsp;An undergraduate academic handbook is going to be a part of this portfolio template, allowing tracking of student learning across the entire degree experience, thus providing opportunity for a year-by-year assessment of specific USOs, rather than limiting the evaluation to the senior capstone.</span></div><div><span>Finally, as we continue to project growth in the Sociology Major Program, the attached article from the Chronicle of Higher Ed gives a brief overview of the potential for a Master's Degree Program. &nbsp;The chart is especially relevant as we continue to work on a tradtitional Sociology Major, as well as a preparatory program for student desiring a Social Work Degree. (see article attachment)</span></div><br><div><span>The program continues the process of moving away from using grades on exams, assignments, and projects. &nbsp;Our outcomes are listed below:</span></div><div><span>PSO #6);&nbsp;We established an academic standard of effort for each letter grade&nbsp;(See the Student Performance Standards attached). &nbsp;The goal was to help them understand that getting the correct answers was not enough to characterize one as an A student. &nbsp;Data for the measure of success was drawn from the Blackboard Learning Management System; students posted evidence of their learning process across the semester. &nbsp;Success was measured by the number of edits and extra (non-assigned evidence) students post from assignments, with a focus on posting that goes beyond minimum posting requirements. &nbsp;The outcomes were encouraging! &nbsp;78% of the Introduction to Sociology classes in SP'08 (N=80, n=65) posted more than the minimum requirements, meaning less missing or late assignments, and compared to the same courses, using the same assignments from SP'07 - rough drafts encouraged, but not required. &nbsp;Less than 50% of the students in two sections created a draft.</span></div><div><span>PSO #4); Continued assessment of written communication skills - The Sociology program continues to put emphasis on quality writing and APA style. &nbsp;We are seeing most of our undergraduate sociology students using proofreading &amp; editing skills. &nbsp;Our intent was to use students self-perception of their Internet, research writing and information literacy skills by completing an anonymous, online survey. &nbsp;This survey was to be used in courses across the SBS disciplines; not enough faculty participated to draw any significant conclusions. &nbsp;In addition, the survey instrument had some serious flaws. &nbsp;We may try this again in the fall using a new survey instrument.</span></div><div><span>PSO #5, the research process; the focus is on library and research skills and information literacy. &nbsp;Students had the opportunity to practice specific elements of research, editing skills, APA, and demonstrate their ability to use the library resources. &nbsp;The MOS was based on evidence from visual essay projects from SOC 345 Social Problems. &nbsp;(See the rubric &amp; PowerPoint samples of A, B &amp; C level work attached.)</span></div><div><span>Also, data was drawn from visual essay projects from SOC 338 Deviant Behavior FA'07, SOC 338 Group Dynamics &amp; Social Movements SP'08 &amp; SOC381ae (Sample of A effort attached). &nbsp; 82% of these upper-division students posted drafts and significant research process evidence (See attachments)</span></div></div></div>

Students are encouraged to pursue a complimentary minor. &nbsp;Students may complete a double major in Psychology and Sociology by substituting overlapping courses. &nbsp;Students may also complete a Psychology or Christian Behavioral Science minor.</span></div><br><span>'12-'13 Sociology Program Final Report</span><br><div><span>&nbsp;1. &nbsp;Final Report: The program evaluated the progress on the move away from straight points grading methodology to a learner-centered set of academic satndards allowing students to decide on the level of effort they wanted to demonstrate beyond the minimum requirements of the assignment.&nbsp;&nbsp;One of the MOAs was the documentation of voluntary rough drafts and edited assignments. &nbsp;In the SOC 213 Introduction to Sociology courses in SP'09, 65% of the students from two sections (N = 80) voluntarily posted assignment efforts that were above minimum requirements&nbsp;(most were from SOC 213 Section B). &nbsp;In addition, 35% completed small outside assignments from the text or from outside reading. &nbsp; Evidence is documented in the Messages feature in Blackboard and will be compiled and analyzed in the Spring of 2010.</span></div><div><span>In SOC 338 Group Dynamics the evidence was also very clear in the group project. &nbsp;90% of the students (N = 16) documented efforts well beyond minimum expectations. &nbsp;Students were required to document their individual research efforts as if they were doing the project individually rather than in a group. &nbsp;The results were seen in impressive powerPoint presentations (examples attached) containing increased depth and breadth. &nbsp; In addition, many of these students self-reflected on the value of the group experience and how it stretched them. &nbsp;(See attachments)</span></div><div><span>The academic portfolio template is still in the earliest stages of development; the goal of having it ready by the end of the SP'09 semester was unrealistic. &nbsp;It will be the foundation for the identification of General Education outcomes in this program. &nbsp;An undergraduate academic handbook is going to be a part of this portfolio template, allowing tracking of student learning across the entire degree experience, thus providing opportunity for a year-by-year assessment of specific USOs, rather than limiting the evaluation to the senior capstone.</span></div><div><span>Finally, as we continue to project growth in the Sociology Major Program, the attached article from the Chronicle of Higher Ed gives a brief overview of the potential for a Master's Degree Program. &nbsp;The chart is especially relevant as we continue to work on a tradtitional Sociology Major, as well as a preparatory program for student desiring a Social Work Degree. (see article attachment)</span></div><br><div><span>The program continues the process of moving away from using grades on exams, assignments, and projects. &nbsp;Our outcomes are listed below:</span></div><div><span>PSO #6);&nbsp;We established an academic standard of effort for each letter grade&nbsp;(See the Student Performance Standards attached). &nbsp;The goal was to help them understand that getting the correct answers was not enough to characterize one as an A student. &nbsp;Data for the measure of success was drawn from the Blackboard Learning Management System; students posted evidence of their learning process across the semester. &nbsp;Success was measured by the number of edits and extra (non-assigned evidence) students post from assignments, with a focus on posting that goes beyond minimum posting requirements. &nbsp;The outcomes were encouraging! &nbsp;78% of the Introduction to Sociology classes in SP'08 (N=80, n=65) posted more than the minimum requirements, meaning less missing or late assignments, and compared to the same courses, using the same assignments from SP'07 - rough drafts encouraged, but not required. &nbsp;Less than 50% of the students in two sections created a draft.</span></div><div><span>PSO #4); Continued assessment of written communication skills - The Sociology program continues to put emphasis on quality writing and APA style. &nbsp;We are seeing most of our undergraduate sociology students using proofreading &amp; editing skills. &nbsp;Our intent was to use students self-perception of their Internet, research writing and information literacy skills by completing an anonymous, online survey. &nbsp;This survey was to be used in courses across the SBS disciplines; not enough faculty participated to draw any significant conclusions. &nbsp;In addition, the survey instrument had some serious flaws. &nbsp;We may try this again in the fall using a new survey instrument.</span></div><div><span>PSO #5, the research process; the focus is on library and research skills and information literacy. &nbsp;Students had the opportunity to practice specific elements of research, editing skills, APA, and demonstrate their ability to use the library resources. &nbsp;The MOS was based on evidence from visual essay projects from SOC 345 Social Problems. &nbsp;(See the rubric &amp; PowerPoint samples of A, B &amp; C level work attached.)</span></div><div><span>Also, data was drawn from visual essay projects from SOC 338 Deviant Behavior FA'07, SOC 338 Group Dynamics &amp; Social Movements SP'08 &amp; SOC381ae (Sample of A effort attached). &nbsp; 82% of these upper-division students posted drafts and significant research process evidence (See attachments)</span></div></div></div>

title: Activity 4
abstract: <div class="abstract-content" data-image-width="1000" data-image-height="5882"><div class="media"><img class="image-resource ng-scope" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e6/1000px-Atmosphere_layers-en.PNG" style="width: 100%;"></div><div class="text"><b>Outer space</b><span>, or simply&nbsp;</span><b>space</b><span>, is the void that exists between&nbsp;</span>celestial bodies<span>, including the&nbsp;</span>Earth<span>.</span><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDainton2001132.E2.80.93133_1-0">[1]</sup><span>&nbsp;It is not completely empty, but consists of a&nbsp;</span>hard vacuum<span>containing a low density of particles: predominantly a&nbsp;</span>plasma<span>&nbsp;of&nbsp;</span>hydrogen<span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;</span>helium<span>, as well as&nbsp;</span>electromagnetic radiation<span>,&nbsp;</span>magnetic fields<span>, and&nbsp;</span>neutrinos<span>. The baseline temperature, as set by the&nbsp;</span>background radiation<span>&nbsp;from the&nbsp;</span>Big Bang<span>, is 2.7&nbsp;</span>kelvin<span>&nbsp;(K).</span><sup id="cite_ref-CBE2008_2-0">[2]</sup><span>&nbsp;Plasma with a density of less than one hydrogen atom per cubic meter and a temperature of millions of kelvin in the&nbsp;</span>space between galaxies<span>&nbsp;accounts for most of the&nbsp;</span>baryonic (ordinary) matter<span>&nbsp;in outer space; local concentrations have condensed into&nbsp;</span>stars<span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;</span>galaxies<span>. In most galaxies, observations provide evidence that 90% of the mass is in an unknown form, called&nbsp;</span>dark matter<span>, which interacts with other matter through&nbsp;</span>gravitational<span>&nbsp;but not&nbsp;</span>electromagnetic<span>&nbsp;forces.</span><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFreedmanKaufmann2005573.2C_599-601_3-0">[3]</sup><sup id="cite_ref-Trimble_1987_4-0">[4]</sup><span>&nbsp;Data indicates that the majority of the&nbsp;</span>mass-energy<span>&nbsp;in the&nbsp;</span>observable Universe<span>is a poorly understood&nbsp;</span>vacuum energy<span>&nbsp;of space which astronomers label&nbsp;</span>dark energy<span>.</span><sup id="cite_ref-nasa_darkenergy_5-0">[5]</sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFreedmanKaufmann2005650-653_6-0">[6]</sup><span>&nbsp;Intergalactic space takes up most of the volume of the&nbsp;</span>Universe<span>, but even galaxies and star systems consist almost entirely of empty space.</span></div></div>

abstract: <div class="abstract-content" data-image-width="1000" data-image-height="5882"><div class="media"><img class="image-resource ng-scope" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e6/1000px-Atmosphere_layers-en.PNG" style="width: 100%;"></div><div class="text"><b>Outer space</b><span>, or simply&nbsp;</span><b>space</b><span>, is the void that exists between&nbsp;</span>celestial bodies<span>, including the&nbsp;</span>Earth<span>.</span><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDainton2001132.E2.80.93133_1-0">[1]</sup><span>&nbsp;It is not completely empty, but consists of a&nbsp;</span>hard vacuum<span>containing a low density of particles: predominantly a&nbsp;</span>plasma<span>&nbsp;of&nbsp;</span>hydrogen<span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;</span>helium<span>, as well as&nbsp;</span>electromagnetic radiation<span>,&nbsp;</span>magnetic fields<span>, and&nbsp;</span>neutrinos<span>. In most galaxies, observations provide evidence that 90% of the mass is in an unknown form, called&nbsp;</span>dark matter<span>, which interacts with other matter through&nbsp;</span>gravitational<span>&nbsp;but not&nbsp;</span>electromagnetic<span>&nbsp;forces.</span><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFreedmanKaufmann2005573.2C_599-601_3-0">[3]</sup><sup id="cite_ref-Trimble_1987_4-0">[4]</sup><span>&nbsp;Data indicates that the majority of the&nbsp;</span>mass-energy<span>&nbsp;in the&nbsp;</span>observable Universe<span>is a poorly understood&nbsp;</span>vacuum energy<span>&nbsp;of space which astronomers label&nbsp;</span>dark energy<span>.</span><sup id="cite_ref-nasa_darkenergy_5-0">[5]</sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFreedmanKaufmann2005650-653_6-0">[6]</sup><span>&nbsp;Intergalactic space takes up most of the volume of the&nbsp;</span>Universe<span>, but even galaxies and star systems consist almost entirely of empty space.</span></div></div>

title: Mastering Communication Assignment
abstract: <div class="abstract-content" data-image-width="1011" data-image-height="911"><div class="media"><img class="image-resource ng-scope" lt-attachment-url-loader="" data-attachment-id="559e95c769702d7be1000012" data-owner="amanda_admin" data-src-target="src" src="https://eportfolio-showcase.s3.amazonaws.com/attachments/61a835b7e5e9e7bbb81ff415f494c3d3.png?AWSAccessKeyId=AKIAISSETHSQKPJC3PRA&amp;Expires=1436642343&amp;Signature=mueTVjE7Y%2FGAsY3eOmSnnQyRmvc%3D" style="width: 100%;"></div><div class="text">Reflection: Mastering Communication<br><span><span>I once read an article for a speech course I was taking that stated that people spend 75% of their time engaged in interpersonal exchanges, and that it should be of no surprise why poor communication is at the root of most problems.&nbsp; When dealing with conflicts among students, I often hear "Oh, I thought....", or "Oh, but I heard you say....", and I have realized that when misunderstandings occur, it is usually due to miscommunication. &nbsp;</span><span><br>As a parent, I know the importance of teacher-parent communication because I send my children to school trusting that someone will teach them what they need to know, but when something happens in the classroom, I like to think the teacher will take the time to inform me.&nbsp; As a pre-service teacher I have experienced the value of&nbsp; communicating with parents, school personnel and fellow teachers because I have been lucky to have worked in environments where the communication lines need to be open and used.<br>During my placement I learned the importance of speaking not only to staff, but to the students to figure out how to better help them. During my time at Tropical Elementary I learned the special role communication plays with ESL students who do not speak English, and the positive impact this can have on what they learn.&nbsp; I never experienced what parents and students who do not speak the language feel, and working with these students opened my eyes to the special provisions provided by the laws on communicating with parents in their native language if they need it.<br>Without the proper communication we are fighting a battle against ignorance with only half of the tools.&nbsp; A teacher must find whatever means possible to communicate with parents, whether it is through a note home, a monthly newsletter, a website, emails or even a phone call.&nbsp; When a teacher shows the parents that she or he is interested in "getting in touch", the parents are more willing to become involved with their student's education.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>I believe I have mastered this practice at the pre-professional level because I have internalized the importance of having the communication skills needed to not only express, but also involve the students, their parents and fellow co-workers.&nbsp; I know how to create newsletters and informative websites, but most importantly I know that without communication I cannot fully help my students.&nbsp; I now know that if I am to be a successful teacher I have to find ways to communicate with those involved with my students, not because it is part of my job, but because it is my duty to do so.</span><span></span></span></div></div>

abstract: <div class="abstract-content" data-image-width="1011" data-image-height="911"><div class="media"><img class="image-resource ng-scope" lt-attachment-url-loader="" data-attachment-id="559e95c769702d7be1000012" data-owner="amanda_admin" data-src-target="src" src="https://eportfolio-showcase.s3.amazonaws.com/attachments/61a835b7e5e9e7bbb81ff415f494c3d3.png?AWSAccessKeyId=AKIAISSETHSQKPJC3PRA&amp;Expires=1436642343&amp;Signature=mueTVjE7Y%2FGAsY3eOmSnnQyRmvc%3D" style="width: 100%;"></div><div class="text">Reflection: Mastering Communication<br><span><span>I once read an article for a speech course I was taking that stated that people spend 75% of their time engaged in interpersonal exchanges, and that it should be of no surprise why poor communication is at the root of most problems.&nbsp; When dealing with conflicts among students, I often hear "Oh, I thought....", or "Oh, but I heard you say....", and I have realized that when misunderstandings occur, it is usually due to miscommunication. &nbsp;</span><span><br>As a parent, I know the importance of teacher-parent communication because I send my children to school trusting that someone will teach them what they need to know, but when something happens in the classroom, I like to think the teacher will take the time to inform me.&nbsp; As a pre-service teacher I have experienced the value of&nbsp; communicating with parents, school personnel and fellow teachers because I have been lucky to have worked in environments where the communication lines need to be open and used.<br>During my placement I learned the importance of speaking not only to staff, but to the students to figure out how to better help them. During my time at Tropical Elementary I learned the special role communication plays with ESL students who do not speak English, and the positive impact this can have on what they learn.&nbsp; I never experienced what parents and students who do not speak the language feel, and working with these students opened my eyes to the special provisions provided by the laws on communicating with parents in their native language if they need it.<br>Without the proper communication we are fighting a battle against ignorance with only half of the tools.&nbsp; A teacher must find whatever means possible to communicate with parents, whether it is through a note home, a monthly newsletter, a website, emails or even a phone call.&nbsp; When a teacher shows the parents that she or he is interested in "getting in touch", the parents are more willing to become involved with their student's education.&nbsp;&nbsp;<br>I believe I have mastered this practice at the pre-professional level because I have internalized the importance of having the communication skills needed to not only express, but also involve the students, their parents and fellow co-workers.&nbsp; I know how to create newsletters and informative websites, but most importantly I know that without communication I cannot fully help my students.&nbsp; I now know that if I am to be a successful teacher I have to find ways to communicate with those involved with my students, not because it is part of my job, but because it is my duty to do so.</span><span></span></span></div></div>

title: Critical Thinking Assignment
abstract: <div class="abstract-content"><div class="text full"><p><span>I was fascinated with this assignment, as I had not yet started to compile these types of strategies. Once during a Science and Math Methods course, Professor Marlene Morales shares a book of CRISS strategies for me and I literately made over one hundred copies of the many strategies listed in it (thank you, Professor Morales!)&nbsp; For this assignment, Dr. Fransisco Brizuela required that we complete this task and I had a wonderful opportunity to continue adding strategies to my personal collection. As such, I needed to do a little research and create a file that was specific to the requirements set by the . I needed to not only add strategies and methodology, but also incorporate different teaching styles and discuss their use and purpose in the classroom. What I learned especially is that a creative teacher needs to include a variety of these into lesson plans in order to keep students interested and learning&nbsp;<span>.</span><o:p></o:p><span></span></span></p><p><span>It was not at all difficult to gather this information, in fact, with the internet, it was simply a case of "Google-ing" and choosing which were those that I felt I could actually use. I love cooperative learning and of course, I included that in there since Dr. Lauren Gach first introduced it to me during my K-5 Practicum. I am far from being an expert, but I thought it is definitely something I can see myself using to help students feel independence and ownership of their own learning. Students need much practice in thinking critically and meta-cognitive reasoning.<span></span></span></p><p><span>What do I plan to do now with this file of resources? Indeed, put it to good use! With these strategies and those that I will continue to add, I hope I can give my students opportunities to do so on a daily basis. If you happen to glance on my lesson plans, you are surely to come across a strategy or two. I want to be the teacher that keeps the classroom in active learning and creates opportunities for the students to participate in the teaching process. The strategies that I included here are just the beginning of what I hope becomes an extensive library for me to implement and develop, as I become an expert teacher. I have already incorporated a few with success, but still far from where I want to be!<span></span></span></p></div></div>

title: Program Portfolio
abstract: <div class="abstract-content" data-image-width="287" data-image-height="460"><div class="media"><img class="image-resource ng-scope" lt-attachment-url-loader="" data-attachment-id="559e8f1769702d7be4000050" data-owner="amanda_admin" data-src-target="src" src="https://eportfolio-showcase.s3.amazonaws.com/attachments/65c8a9effde45046390cceb972819dde.jpg?AWSAccessKeyId=AKIAISSETHSQKPJC3PRA&amp;Expires=1436548724&amp;Signature=d8Q6fZmyv5%2FHM9UbMP1iq9uGb6A%3D" style="width: 100%;"></div><div class="text">"Education is learning what you didn't even know you didn't know" -DANIEL J. BOORSTIN<br><span><b></b><span><div><span><span>ESE Pre-service Teacher<br>LiveText State College<span><br><span>School of Education<br><span><span><span><span><span>(312) 555-2633 Home<br>(312) 555-5239 Cell<br><span><span><span><span><span><span>stu.dent@livetext.edu<span><span><span><br></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></div><br><span><span><span><span><strong><em>About Me:</em></strong><span><span><span><span><div><span><span><span><span><span>The first thing you should know about me is that I am not only a Senior at LiveText State College's School of Education, but I am a computer graphic artist and&nbsp; web designer.&nbsp; I am a father of 4 wonderful children, and I am looking forward to graduating and working to help change students' lives.&nbsp;<br><span><span><br><strong><em><span>Education as a Career:<br><span></span></span></em></strong><span><span><span><span><span>Although I had originally planned to work towards a degree in Psychology, after getting tired of complaining so much about the "system" I finally gave in and decided to become part of the solution. I have chosen Exceptional Student Education because I believe I can make a difference in more than academics. I believe I can reach children who have severe emotional and behavior problems just as easily as I can reach the gifted children, and as I complete my journey through LiveText State College I am sure I will find where I belong<span><span>.&nbsp;</span><span>I plan to pursue&nbsp;a Master's Degree &nbsp;in Exceptional Student Education and Reading, and a Doctorate in Psychology.<span><br><span><br><span><span></span></span><span><em><span><strong><em>Personal Vision:<br></em></strong><span></span></span></em><span>At the Doctorate level I see myself working with our students, teachers and parents to figure out just what "does" work.&nbsp; And, since I am musical, artistic and a Multiple Intelligences advocate, I see myself working (at some level) on the "Artful Thinking" Project Zero Research Program.&nbsp; I have an incredible love for knowledge and I see myself spending my life helping, not only the children who get left behind, but all children.<br><span><span><br><span><span>Although I do not see myself in a classroom for 20 years,&nbsp;I do see myself creating educational programs at the State, if not at the Federal Level.&nbsp; Also, since I am a writer, I see myself writing several teacher "helper" books.&nbsp;&nbsp;<span><span>I believe the current education system needs to be transformed from what it was 200 years ago to what it needs to be today, and I plan to spend my life working on that.<span><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></div></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></div></div>

title: Program Portfolio
abstract: <div class="abstract-content" data-image-width="287" data-image-height="460"><div class="media"><img class="image-resource ng-scope" lt-attachment-url-loader="" data-attachment-id="559e8f1769702d7be4000050" data-owner="amanda_admin" data-src-target="src" src="https://eportfolio-showcase.s3.amazonaws.com/attachments/65c8a9effde45046390cceb972819dde.jpg?AWSAccessKeyId=AKIAISSETHSQKPJC3PRA&amp;Expires=1436548724&amp;Signature=d8Q6fZmyv5%2FHM9UbMP1iq9uGb6A%3D" style="width: 100%;"></div><div class="text">"Education is learning what you didn't even know you didn't know" -DANIEL J. BOORSTIN<br><span><b></b><span><div><span><span>ESE Pre-service Teacher<br>LiveText State College<span><br><span>School of Education<br><span><span><span><span><span>(312) 555-2633 Home<br>(312) 555-5239 Cell<br><span><span><span><span><span><span>stu.dent@livetext.edu<span><span><span><br></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></div><br><span><span><span><span><strong><em>About Me:</em></strong><span><span><span><span><div><span><span><span><span><span>The first thing you should know about me is that I am not only a Senior at LiveText State College's School of Education, but I am a computer graphic artist and&nbsp; web designer.&nbsp; I am a father of 4 wonderful children, and I am looking forward to graduating and working to help change students' lives.&nbsp;<br><span><span><br><strong><em><span>Education as a Career:<br><span></span></span></em></strong><span><span><span><span><span>Although I had originally planned to work towards a degree in Psychology, after getting tired of complaining so much about the "system" I finally gave in and decided to become part of the solution. I have chosen Exceptional Student Education because I believe I can make a difference in more than academics. I believe I can reach children who have severe emotional and behavior problems just as easily as I can reach the gifted children, and as I complete my journey through LiveText State College I am sure I will find where I belong<span><span>.&nbsp;</span><span>I plan to pursue&nbsp;a Master's Degree &nbsp;in Exceptional Student Education and Reading, and a Doctorate in Psychology.<span><br><span><br><span><span></span></span><span><em><span><strong><em>Personal Vision:<br></em></strong><span></span></span></em><span>At the Doctorate level I see myself working with our students, teachers and parents to figure out just what "does" work.&nbsp; And, since I am musical, artistic and a Multiple Intelligences advocate, I see myself working (at some level) on the "Artful Thinking" Project Zero Research Program.&nbsp; I have an incredible love for knowledge and I see myself spending my life helping, not only the children who get left behind, but all children.<br><span><span><br><span><span>Although I do not see myself in a classroom for 20 years,&nbsp;I do see myself creating educational programs at the State, if not at the Federal Level.&nbsp; Also, since I am a writer, I see myself writing several teacher "helper" books.&nbsp;&nbsp;<span><span>I believe the current education system needs to be transformed from what it was 200 years ago to what it needs to be today, and I plan to spend my life working on that.<span><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></div></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></div></div>

title: Test Activity 102816
abstract: <div class="abstract-content"><div class="text full">Personal Journey<br>In 1992, I was starting my first semester at college, this in spite of the fact that I really stumbled into the college experience. My parents were foreigners, and they knew nothing of the college entrance process.<br>So there I am, standing in line for registration, having looked through the vast course catalog for classes that piqued my interest...genetics, ceramics, British writers...<br>Only to be rudely awakened by Ida...here's our recommendation...comp 101 &amp; public speaking...<br>Those were not the classes I wanted and in order to take the classes I did want I needed to talk to the chair of the department.<br>I came prepared with my pre-e-portfolio, portfolio of senior English comp papers.<br>He actually let me into British Writers, reluctantly, and I was lucky to get a B as he predicted.<br>It wasn't until many years later that I came across that portfolio of senior year English papers again. Wow. That argument with the chair was bold, and the evidence I presented pretty weak. And it was only in that reflection many years later that I was able to actually assess my growth and progress.<br></div></div>

title: Activity 1
abstract: <div class="abstract-content" data-image-width="440" data-image-height="293"><div class="media"><img class="image-resource" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/3/36/Large_bonfire.jpg/440px-Large_bonfire.jpg" style="width: 100%;"></div><div class="text"><p><b>Fire</b>&nbsp;is the rapid&nbsp;oxidation&nbsp;of a material in the&nbsp;exothermic&nbsp;chemical process of&nbsp;combustion, releasing&nbsp;heat,&nbsp;light, and various reaction&nbsp;products.<sup id="cite_ref-1">[1]</sup>&nbsp;Slower oxidative processes like&nbsp;rusting&nbsp;or&nbsp;digestion&nbsp;are not included by this definition.</p><p>The&nbsp;&nbsp;is the visible portion of the fire. If hot enough, the gases may become ionized to produce&nbsp;plasma.<sup id="cite_ref-2">[2]</sup>&nbsp;Depending on the substances alight, and any impurities outside, the&nbsp;color&nbsp;of the flame and the fire's&nbsp;intensity&nbsp;will be different.</p><p>Fire in its most common form can result in&nbsp;conflagration, which has the potential to cause physical damage through&nbsp;burning. Fire is an important process that affects ecological systems across the globe. The positive effects of fire include stimulating growth and maintaining various ecological systems. Fire has been used by humans for cooking, generating heat, signaling, and propulsion purposes. The negative effects of fire include water contamination, soil erosion, atmospheric pollution and hazard to life and property.<sup id="cite_ref-3">[3]</sup></p><br><div>Figure 1. &nbsp;A fire.</div><br><div>Figure 2. Another fire.</div><br><p>Fires start when a&nbsp;flammable&nbsp;and/or a combustible&nbsp;material, in combination with a sufficient quantity of an&nbsp;oxidizer&nbsp;such as oxygen gas or another oxygen-rich compound (though non-oxygen oxidizers exist that can replace oxygen), is exposed to a source of&nbsp;heat&nbsp;or ambient&nbsp;temperature&nbsp;above the&nbsp;flash point&nbsp;for thefuel/oxidizer mix, and is able to sustain a rate of rapid oxidation that produces a&nbsp;chain reaction. This is commonly called the&nbsp;fire tetrahedron. Fire cannot exist without all of these elements in place and in the right proportions. For example, a flammable liquid will start burning only if the fuel and oxygen are in the right proportions. Some fuel-oxygen mixes may require a&nbsp;catalyst, a substance that is not directly involved in any&nbsp;chemical&nbsp;reaction during combustion, but which enables the reactants to combust more readily.</p><p>Once ignited, a chain reaction must take place whereby fires can sustain their own heat by the further release of heat energy in the process of combustion and may propagate, provided there is a continuous supply of an oxidizer and fuel.</p><p>If the oxidizer is oxygen from the surrounding air, the presence of a force of&nbsp;gravity, or of some similar force caused by acceleration, is necessary to produceconvection, which removes combustion products and brings a supply of oxygen to the fire. Without gravity, a fire rapidly surrounds itself with its own combustion products and non-oxidizing gases from the air, which exclude oxygen and&nbsp;extinguish&nbsp;it. Because of this, the risk of fire in a&nbsp;spacecraft&nbsp;is small when it is&nbsp;coastingin inertial flight. Of course, this does not apply if oxygen is supplied to the fire by some process other than thermal convection.</p><br><span>Has your life ever been changed irreversibly by a fire? &nbsp;Who started the fire?</span><br><span>(Hint: We didn't start the fire.)</span></div></div>

title: Activity 2
abstract: <div class="abstract-content" data-image-width="1000" data-image-height="5882"><div class="media"><img class="image-resource" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/e/e6/1000px-Atmosphere_layers-en.PNG" style="width: 100%;"></div><div class="text"><b>Outer space</b><span>, or simply&nbsp;</span><b>space</b><span>, is the void that exists between&nbsp;</span>celestial bodies<span>, including the&nbsp;</span>Earth<span>.</span><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEDainton2001132.E2.80.93133_1-0">[1]</sup><span>&nbsp;It is not completely empty, but consists of a&nbsp;</span>hard vacuum<span>containing a low density of particles: predominantly a&nbsp;</span>plasma<span>&nbsp;of&nbsp;</span>hydrogen<span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;</span>helium<span>, as well as&nbsp;</span>electromagnetic radiation<span>,&nbsp;</span>magnetic fields<span>, and&nbsp;</span>neutrinos<span>. The baseline temperature, as set by the&nbsp;</span>background radiation<span>&nbsp;from the&nbsp;</span>Big Bang<span>, is 2.7&nbsp;</span>kelvin<span>&nbsp;(K).</span><sup id="cite_ref-CBE2008_2-0">[2]</sup><span>&nbsp;Plasma with a density of less than one hydrogen atom per cubic meter and a temperature of millions of kelvin in the&nbsp;</span>space between galaxies<span>&nbsp;accounts for most of the&nbsp;</span>baryonic (ordinary) matter<span>&nbsp;in outer space; local concentrations have condensed into&nbsp;</span>stars<span>&nbsp;and&nbsp;</span>galaxies<span>. In most galaxies, observations provide evidence that 90% of the mass is in an unknown form, called&nbsp;</span>dark matter<span>, which interacts with other matter through&nbsp;</span>gravitational<span>&nbsp;but not&nbsp;</span>electromagnetic<span>&nbsp;forces.</span><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFreedmanKaufmann2005573.2C_599-601_3-0">[3]</sup><sup id="cite_ref-Trimble_1987_4-0">[4]</sup><span>&nbsp;Data indicates that the majority of the&nbsp;</span>mass-energy<span>&nbsp;in the&nbsp;</span>observable Universe<span>is a poorly understood&nbsp;</span>vacuum energy<span>&nbsp;of space which astronomers label&nbsp;</span>dark energy<span>.</span><sup id="cite_ref-nasa_darkenergy_5-0">[5]</sup><sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEFreedmanKaufmann2005650-653_6-0">[6]</sup><span>&nbsp;Intergalactic space takes up most of the volume of the&nbsp;</span>Universe<span>, but even galaxies and star systems consist almost entirely of empty space.</span><br><p>There is no firm boundary where space begins. However the&nbsp;Krmn line, at an altitude of 100&nbsp;km (62&nbsp;mi) above&nbsp;sea level,<sup id="cite_ref-FOOTNOTEO.27Leary200984_7-0">[7]</sup>&nbsp;is conventionally used as the start of outer space in space treaties and for aerospace records keeping. The framework for international&nbsp;space law&nbsp;was established by the&nbsp;Outer Space Treaty, which was passed by the&nbsp;United Nations&nbsp;in 1967. This treaty precludes any claims of national sovereignty and permits all states to freely explore outer space. In 1979, theMoon Treaty&nbsp;made the surfaces of objects such as planets, as well as the orbital space around these bodies, the jurisdiction of the international community. Despite the drafting of UN resolutions for the peaceful uses of outer space,&nbsp;anti-satellite weapons&nbsp;have been tested in Earth orbit.</p><p>Humans began the physical exploration of space during the 20th century with the advent of high-altitude&nbsp;balloon flights, followed by manned&nbsp;rocket launches.&nbsp;Earth orbit&nbsp;was first achieved by&nbsp;Yuri Gagarin&nbsp;of the Soviet Union in 1961 and&nbsp;unmanned spacecraft&nbsp;have since reached all of the known&nbsp;planets&nbsp;in the&nbsp;Solar System. Achieving&nbsp;low Earth orbit&nbsp;requires a minimum velocity of 28,100&nbsp;km/h (17,500&nbsp;mph), much faster than any conventional aircraft. Outer space represents a challenging environment for human exploration because of the dual hazards of vacuum and&nbsp;radiation.&nbsp;Microgravity&nbsp;has a negative effect on human&nbsp;physiology, causing&nbsp;muscle atrophy&nbsp;and&nbsp;bone loss.&nbsp;Space travel&nbsp;has been limited to low Earth orbit and the&nbsp;Moon&nbsp;for manned flight, and the&nbsp;vicinity of the Solar System&nbsp;for unmanned vehicles. In August 2012,&nbsp;Voyager 1&nbsp;became the first man-made craft to enter interstellar space.</p><br><div>Figure 2. &nbsp;A picture of something you might find in outer space.</div><br><span>Do you think you will ever go to outer space? &nbsp;Why?</span><br><span>Do you prefer astronauts or cosmonauts? &nbsp;Why?</span></div></div>

title: Activity 3
abstract: <div class="abstract-content"><div class="text full"><span>Annual Assessment of Student Outcomes</span><br><div><span>School of Behavioral Sciences BA in Sociology</span><br></div><div><span>BA Sociology - (44 units)</span></div><div><span>The Sociology major prepares graduates for employment in social service careers, and for graduate study in Sociology, Criminology, Social Work, and Anthropology. &nbsp;Students select at least one area of concentration within the major. Students are encouraged to pursue a complimentary minor. &nbsp;Students may complete a double major in Psychology and Sociology by substituting overlapping courses. &nbsp;Students may also complete a Psychology or Christian Behavioral Science minor.</span></div><br><span>'12-'13 Sociology Program Final Report</span><br><div><span>&nbsp;1. &nbsp;Final Report: The program evaluated the progress on the move away from straight points grading methodology to a learner-centered set of academic satndards allowing students to decide on the level of effort they wanted to demonstrate beyond the minimum requirements of the assignment.&nbsp;&nbsp;One of the MOAs was the documentation of voluntary rough drafts and edited assignments. &nbsp;In the SOC 213 Introduction to Sociology courses in SP'09, 65% of the students from two sections (N = 80) voluntarily posted assignment efforts that were above minimum requirements&nbsp;(most were from SOC 213 Section B). &nbsp;In addition, 35% completed small outside assignments from the text or from outside reading. &nbsp; Evidence is documented in the Messages feature in Blackboard and will be compiled and analyzed in the Spring of 2010.</span></div><div><span>In SOC 338 Group Dynamics the evidence was also very clear in the group project. &nbsp;90% of the students (N = 16) documented efforts well beyond minimum expectations. &nbsp;Students were required to document their individual research efforts as if they were doing the project individually rather than in a group. &nbsp;The results were seen in impressive powerPoint presentations (examples attached) containing increased depth and breadth. &nbsp; In addition, many of these students self-reflected on the value of the group experience and how it stretched them. &nbsp;(See attachments)</span></div><div><span>The academic portfolio template is still in the earliest stages of development; the goal of having it ready by the end of the SP'09 semester was unrealistic. &nbsp;It will be the foundation for the identification of General Education outcomes in this program. &nbsp;An undergraduate academic handbook is going to be a part of this portfolio template, allowing tracking of student learning across the entire degree experience, thus providing opportunity for a year-by-year assessment of specific USOs, rather than limiting the evaluation to the senior capstone.</span></div><div><span>Finally, as we continue to project growth in the Sociology Major Program, the attached article from the Chronicle of Higher Ed gives a brief overview of the potential for a Master's Degree Program. &nbsp;The chart is especially relevant as we continue to work on a tradtitional Sociology Major, as well as a preparatory program for student desiring a Social Work Degree. (see article attachment)</span></div><br><div><span>The program continues the process of moving away from using grades on exams, assignments, and projects. &nbsp;Our outcomes are listed below:</span></div><div><span>PSO #6);&nbsp;We established an academic standard of effort for each letter grade&nbsp;(See the Student Performance Standards attached). &nbsp;The goal was to help them understand that getting the correct answers was not enough to characterize one as an A student. &nbsp;Data for the measure of success was drawn from the Blackboard Learning Management System; students posted evidence of their learning process across the semester. &nbsp;Success was measured by the number of edits and extra (non-assigned evidence) students post from assignments, with a focus on posting that goes beyond minimum posting requirements. &nbsp;The outcomes were encouraging! &nbsp;78% of the Introduction to Sociology classes in SP'08 (N=80, n=65) posted more than the minimum requirements, meaning less missing or late assignments, and compared to the same courses, using the same assignments from SP'07 - rough drafts encouraged, but not required. &nbsp;Less than 50% of the students in two sections created a draft.</span></div><div><span>PSO #4); Continued assessment of written communication skills - The Sociology program continues to put emphasis on quality writing and APA style. &nbsp;We are seeing most of our undergraduate sociology students using proofreading &amp; editing skills. &nbsp;Our intent was to use students self-perception of their Internet, research writing and information literacy skills by completing an anonymous, online survey. &nbsp;This survey was to be used in courses across the SBS disciplines; not enough faculty participated to draw any significant conclusions. &nbsp;In addition, the survey instrument had some serious flaws. &nbsp;We may try this again in the fall using a new survey instrument.</span></div><div><span>PSO #5, the research process; the focus is on library and research skills and information literacy. &nbsp;Students had the opportunity to practice specific elements of research, editing skills, APA, and demonstrate their ability to use the library resources. &nbsp;The MOS was based on evidence from visual essay projects from SOC 345 Social Problems. &nbsp;(See the rubric &amp; PowerPoint samples of A, B &amp; C level work attached.)</span></div><div><span>Also, data was drawn from visual essay projects from SOC 338 Deviant Behavior FA'07, SOC 338 Group Dynamics &amp; Social Movements SP'08 &amp; SOC381ae (Sample of A effort attached). &nbsp; 82% of these upper-division students posted drafts and significant research process evidence (See attachments)</span></div></div></div>
